  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" class="fn" id="_edn1">1</a> Rule 1.7 states, in pertinent
  part, "Loyalty is an essential element in the lawyer's relationship to a client. Therefore, a lawyer shall not
  represent a client if the representative of that client may be materially limited by the lawyer's responsibilities to
  another client or to a third person, or by the lawyer's own interest..."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">Rule 8.4(d) provides, "It is professional misconduct for a lawyer to engage in conduct that
  is prejudicial to the administration of justice."</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2" class="fn" id="_edn2">2</a> A duty owed by every Louisiana
  lawyer, Rules of Professional Conduct 8.1(c) and 8.4(g)</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3" class="fn" id="_edn3">3</a> Where he will be in a class with
  dozens of other lawyers who could be his grandchildren .</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4" class="fn" id="_edn4">4</a> See f.n. #2</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5" class="fn" id="_edn5">5</a> There is no evidence in the
  record that the Respondent's interest actually was in conflict with or adverse to his brother's interest in the
  succession; thus, there may not have been a conflict of interest as defined by Rule 1.7.  However, according to
  <i><u>In re Lieberman</u>, 675 So.2d 272 (La. 1996),</i> " although the Board may reject proposed consent discipline
  as too lenient, when respondent and Disciplinary Counsel have agreed that a violation occurred, it may not reject
  consent discipline claiming that there was no violation."   Therefore, the Board cannot conclude that there was no
  violation involving a conflict of interest.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6" class="fn" id="_edn6">6</a> There was a representation at
  the Board Panel hearing that the Sheriff may not have received the temporary restraining order prohibiting the sale
  due to an unexpected delay with the Clerk of Court.  It is unknown whether Respondent had a copy of the temporary
  restraining order with him on the day of the sale and the altercation with Steven Raacke.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7" class="fn" id="_edn7">7</a> The Board was not provided with
  any supporting material (citation, transcript, etc.) from the contempt proceeding before Judge Hughes.  Rather the
  contempt was alleged in the Formal Charges and admitted by Respondent in his answer.</p>
